post_cb({"29800268": {"ParentId": "29799766", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "3", "Body": "<p>The definition violates C++14 [class.static.data] \u00a79.4.2/2. Emphasis mine: </p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_29799766_29800268_0\">In the definition at namespace scope, the name of the static data\n  member shall be qualified by <strong>its class name</strong> using the <code>::</code>\n  operator.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>A more recent version of GCC (on <a href=\"http://coliru.stacked-crooked.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Coliru</a>) behaves the same regardless of the qualifier. You can defeat the error on GCC with <code>-fpermissive</code>, but note that you're still only defining one object, belonging to the base class.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "153285", "LastEditorUserId": "153285", "LastEditDate": "2015-04-22T14:14:03.563", "Id": "29800268", "Score": "4", "CreationDate": "2015-04-22T14:10:48.143", "LastActivityDate": "2015-04-22T14:14:03.563"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_29799766_29800268_0": {"section_id": 5907, "quality": 1.0, "length": 13}}, "n3337": {"so_29799766_29800268_0": {"section_id": 5679, "quality": 1.0, "length": 13}}, "n4659": {"so_29799766_29800268_0": {"section_id": 7389, "quality": 1.0, "length": 13}}}, "29799766": {"CommentCount": "3", "AcceptedAnswerId": "29800268", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "3305546", "CreationDate": "2015-04-22T13:53:57.040", "LastActivityDate": "2015-04-22T14:14:03.563", "LastEditDate": "2015-04-22T14:11:17.127", "ViewCount": "243", "FavoriteCount": "0", "Title": "Initialize the protected static member from the subclass", "Id": "29799766", "Score": "4", "Body": "<p>I want to know if it's possible to initialize a protected static member from the subclass.<br>\nFor example,<br/></br></p>\n<pre><code>// head file\nclass Test\n{\nprotected:\n    static int i;\n};\nclass Test2 : public Test{};\n\n//cpp file\n#include \"headfile.h\"\nint Test2::i = 1;\n</code></pre>\n<p>As you see, when I initialize this static member (i), I use the subclass name (Test2).<br>\nTo my surprise, I tested this code with visual studio 2013 and it worked without error. But if I tried it with Netbeans(gcc11) under Linux and I got an hint error:<br>\n<code>unable to resolve the identifier i</code><br>\nThen I compiled it, the error message is:<br>\n<code>error: ISO C++ does not permit \u2018Test::i\u2019 to be defined as \u2018Test2::i\u2019 [-fpermissive]</code></br></br></br></br></p>\n<p>Now if I change the protected into public for the <code>static int i</code> in the class Test, the error will disappear.<br/></p>\n<p>I am confused... This is my first time that I found two different results with gcc and vs.</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><static><initialization>", "OwnerUserId": "3305546", "AnswerCount": "1"}});